The species was first described by [[Thomas C. Jerdon|Jerdon]] in 1840 under the name of ''Anthus rufescens'', a name already used by Temminck for a different species. Blyth referred to it under the name of ''Anthus montanus''. These are however invalid names and it was redescribed under replacement name of ''A. nilghiriensis'' by [[Richard Bowdler Sharpe]] in 1885.<ref>{{cite book|author=Sharpe, R.B.|title=Catalogue of the Passeriformes, or perching birds, in the collection of the British Museum. Fringilliformes. Part 1.|year=1885|pages=550–551|url=https://archive.org/stream/catalogueofbirds10brit#page/550/mode/1up}}</ref>

The Nilgiri pipit is closely related to the tree pipits and is a sister to the clade containing ''[[Anthus trivialis]]'' and ''[[Anthus hodgsoni]]'' from which it diverged in the [[Pliocene]].<ref name=phyl>{{cite journal|doi=10.1098/rsos.140364 |doi-access=free|pmid=26064613 |title=Dramatic niche shifts and morphological change in two insular bird species |journal=Royal Society Open Science |volume=2 |issue=3 |article-number=140364 |year=2015 |last1=Alstrom |first1=P. |last2=Jonsson |first2=K. A. |last3=Fjeldsa |first3=J. |last4=Odeen |first4=A. |last5=Ericson |first5=P. G. P. |last6=Irestedt |first6=M. |pmc=4448822|bibcode=2015RSOS....240364A }}</ref>

== Distribution and habitat ==
[[File:Nilgiri pipit from Perumalmalai peak, Kodaikanal Wildlife Sactuary.jpg|thumb|Nilgiri pipit in [[Kodaikanal Wildlife Sanctuary]]]]
The Nilgiri pipit is closely associated with short [[montane grassland]]s interspersed with [[marsh]]y grounds and small streams mostly in hill slopes above {{convert|1000|m}} in the Ponmudi hills and above {{convert|1500|m}} in the Nilgiris, [[Palani]] and High Ranges.<ref name=hbk/> They have also been claimed to occur in the [[Kalakkad Mundanthurai Tiger Reserve]]<ref>{{cite journal|author=Johnsingh A.J.T.  |year=2001|title=The Kalakad–Mundanthurai Tiger Reserve: A global heritage of biological diversity| journal=Current Science|volume=80|issue=3|pages=378–388|url=http://www.ias.ac.in/currsci/feb102001/378.pdf }}</ref> but a 2014 study suggests that the species is restricted to the high altitude grassy peaks of the Nilgiris and the Anamalais. Museum specimens exist from the [[Palani]] ranges but habitat changes may have led to its reduction or extirpation as the species was not found in surveys in the 21st century.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Reassessment of the distribution and threat status of the Western Ghats endemic bird, Nilgiri Pipit Anthus nilghiriensis|journal=Current Science|volume=107|issue=4|pages=622–630 |year=2014 |url=http://www.currentscience.ac.in/Volumes/107/04/0622.pdf|author1=Robin, V.V. |author2=C.K.Vishnudas |author3=Uma Ramakrishnan|author-link3=Uma Ramakrishnan |name-list-style=amp }}</ref>

==Behaviour==
Nilgiri pipits are found singly or in pairs. When disturbed they usually fly into a low bush or tree.<ref name=pcr/> They breed in summer from April to July. The nest is a cup of grass in short grass. The clutch consists of two to three grey brown speckled eggs.<ref name=hbk/> They feed on grass seeds and insects with invertebrates becoming more important during the breeding season.<ref name="iucn status 12 November 2021" />

==Status==
The world population is estimated to be about 4000 birds based on a density estimate of about 0.1 birds per hectare in suitable habitat. The grassland habitat is threatened by wattle plantations and the colonization of grasslands by species such as broom (''[[Cytisus scoparius]]'') in the Nilgiris and by fire.<ref name="iucn status 12 November 2021" /><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/SACON1998/SACON1998-99#page/n25/mode/2up/|page=23|title=SACON annual report|year=1998|author=Anonymous|publisher=SACON, Coimbatore}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Zarri, A. A.|author2=A. R. Rahmani|author3=M. J. Behan|name-list-style=amp| year= 2006| title= Habitat modifications by scotch broom ''Cytisus scoparius'' invasion of grasslands of the upper Nilgiris in India| journal= Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society |volume=103|pages=356–365}}</ref>

